  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrating MHPSS Across Cordaid Thematics (IMPACT) Uganda</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Generate grounded, programme-relevant insights on the MHPSS needs of (S)GBV survivors in West Nile, and MHPSS needs of refugee and host family communities 
2. Co-produce with refugee and host communities actionable solutions for delivering  a package that integrates MHPSS support to (S)GBV survivors alongside other social support services.  
3. Iteratively test solutions and  opportunities for scale-up where possible, documenting and jointly analysing results with refugee and host communities
4. Inform and influence the development of policy frameworks in Uganda and globally that support constructive linkages between mental health and access to justice and health care for (S)GBV survivors</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">SGBV Survivors are the primary targets. other key stake holders will involve; health sector, legal aid providers, Refugee Welfare Council (RWC) system, Local Councils and Local Council Courts (LCCs), UNHCR and protection agencies, and Justice Law and Order Sector (JLOS) institutions.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Integrating MHPSS Across Cordaid Thematics (IMPACT) project is an upcoming project that responds directly to recognition that the impact of diverse Cordaid interventions in support of vulnerable women and men in fragile and conflict-affected contexts will be inadequate and unsustainable if pervasive mental health needs are left unaddressed. The project will attempt to show linkages between MHPSS and humanitarian work; demonstrate intersections between mental health and psychosocial wellbeing and justice and security sectors and clearly bring out the importance of integrating MHPSS as part of the continuum of care for survivors of GBV. 

Cordaid already incorporates MHPSS as part of an integrated approach in West Nile region, but aspires to develop an integrated, adaptive package of interventions that connects MHPSS activities to  a continuum of services for (S)GBV survivors in Uganda. The action research will constitute IMPACT phase 1 of the Uganda trajectory (2020) of a multi-country project and inform Cordaid planning for (and the enabling environment of) IMPACT phase 2 (piloting) will largely consist of piloting the models that would have been developed in phase 1 to ascertain efficacy of the project design, identify change elements and fine tune the interventions</narrative>
  </description>
